commentBody:
@Puzzlemucker 

I recently solved a Byron Walden Thursday puzzle from November, 2005. The revealer was “Divided Capitals” and the theme answers incorporated the names of world capitals, with those letters circled. 

I was impressed that he managed to work Caracas into the grid, and it would have been a fine Tuesday or Wednesday puzzle. But it wasn’t a Thursday puzzle of the type we’ve seen in the past few years.

@Will 

The line labeled “From the Archives” or something like that?

I hadn’t noticed that was gone from the updated app. It’s too bad; they used to suggest some good puzzles.

@Eric Hougland 

I recently complained about the new Games interface, but something weird happened a few days ago. It's back to the way it was, including the From the Archives suggestions.  Like I said. Weird.  
Now if we could only turn off the pop up screen that congrats me and tells me how long it took me to solve the puzzle EVERY SINGLE TIME  I open up the puzzle, I would be much happier.

@MA Took me awhile to get there tonight.

Maybe this will help - *Begin becomes (Be)Gin, or put another way, a Gin that starts with "B".  So the solve Beefeaters.  Similarly, *Emirate becomes (Em)Irate, or a word/phrase for Irate that starts with "M".  So the solve "Mad as hell"

Hope this helps!

@Barry Ancona 
Sorry to disagree.  The Draft is an NBA PR event. There is nothing sporting about it. There is no competitive aspect to it whatsoever. Just because an event is administered by a multi billion dollar business that also runs a sports league does not make that event a sports event.

A more correct answer to the clue would be NBA Final

@Petunia 

We're actually talking about the Thursday puzzle here now. The puzzles come out at 10 p.m. Eastern time Monday through Friday, and 6 p.m. on Saturday and Sunday. So, if you wanted to discuss the Wednesday puzzle, you need to go to:

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/02/20/crosswords/daily-puzzle-2024-02-21.html#commentsContainer" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/2024/02/20/crosswords/daily-puzzle-2024-02-21.html#commentsContainer</a>

@Deb Amlen and @Lewis,

Thank you so much for bolstering my ego and breaking my fall!
😉

@Wes Dude. Start with Mondays and Tuesdays.  As a neophyte they will be less tricky.

Also, read the explainer.  It gives context on what each day's puzzle is supposed to be.

You are angry because you misunders tand what a Thursday puzzle is supposed to be.  Th is is supposed to be oblique\obscure\punned.

@Ted B 
True. But that's not the clue, which says Sports Event.  And insofar as the answer is an event related to a sport, it is correct.  

I personally would rather watch paint dry, but that's neither here nor there.

@Helen Wright 
KALES is "an Americanism of convenience," meaning "we made it up, Solvers, so grin and bear it"



Wet dog walk, eh?  Just one more reason to be A Cat Person!

@Wr 

Because if JAKE had been clued as “Actor Gyllenhaal” or
“Boxer LaMotta,” there would have been complaints about “too many proper names.”

@Steve L 

Agreed. The New Yorker’s label of “beginner-friendly” is right on the mark today. There are even a few examples of Ms. Weintraub’s wit in the clues. 

The puzzle has a few too many government agency acronyms for my taste, but they are all well-known entities.

@Andrzej I knew you'd check in. I've lived in Germany for 23 years but still there are loads of things I'll never understand because I didn't grow up here. That's the life of a stranger in a strange land, and I accept it. I'd have the same problems with a German crossword puzzle. Sadly, there isn't an equivalent to the NYTXW, but if there were it would understandably be geared to a German readership. I can't begrudge them that.

And as I've mentioned before, even though I grew up and was educated in the US, lived in five cities in three states and consumed the English language in all its facets for 46 years before leaving those shores, I don't know NBA trivia any better than you do. Well, maybe slightly better. And television shows, pop stars and car brands take all the fun out of it for me. In that respect, you're not alone. But that's life! 

I didn't love today's either but I did know the word COPACETIC because Duke Ellington used it. There's always a bright side. 😁

@Cat Lady Margaret

Works for me! 

I have known people who are so unmusical that their air guitars are out-of-tune.

@Nancy 

As you are a disciple of the Rex, I am surprised how liberally you use the term Natick.  I guess a Natick is anything cross the solver doesn't know, and feels like it is impossible that anyone would be expected to know it.  Definitions evolve I guess...

"Pop culture" I knew you gleefully ignore, but Arabica beans are a Natick-worthy?  To each their own.

@Mean Old Lady 
Glad to hear things going well with daughter. 
 Drinking tea at a Boston Tea Party party? So WRONG! Boycott tea as the patriots did back then!

@Steve 

Well, then...you really ought to check out Stoners' Film Festival: Sunday, June 2, 2019.

It's a real hoot.

@Cele 

Congratulations!

I’m sure it’s just the first of many solo Thursdays.

@Jim in Forest Hills 

My theory about Thursday puzzles is that once you spot the trick, they’re usually not too difficult. 

Of course, sometimes it takes a while to spot the trick.

@Kate 

I'm glad your husband is home. Was it he who was having a hip replacement replacement?

In any case, I hope he has a quick and thorough recovery. Best of luck to you both.

@Kate 

You're welcome. 

That's more surgeries than anyone should have to go through.

@R.J. Smith 

30+ years ago, I scored a job with the Texas Legislature. I landed a position that fit me really well.

Thanks for your contributions towards my salary and retirement benefits.

@Argee the Runt 

7D: “Neat as a PIN” is an idiom that apparently is not as well-known as the constructor and editors thought. 

You can find your in-progress puzzles if you go to the main puzzle page in a browser. I emailed the NYTGames team to complain about that loss of functionality in the games app. I don’t know why they did that.

@Grant - Believe it or not, I actually know an accordion tuner. He's actually a very talented pianist and piano repairman/tuner, in great demand, but he does accordions on the side. 

I don't think anyone could make a living as an accordion tuner, because a well cared-for accordion doesn't need tuning very often, and there are far fewer of them than there are pianos. 

He tunes pianos mostly by ear (using tuning forks) but uses one of those sound interference detector thingies for the accordions. He feels using a machine to tune a piano precisely makes it too perfect; it sounds dad to him. I wonder if David Connell would agree. For the accordion, with so many harmonics, it doesn't make much of a difference, so he uses the electronic helper.

@David B 

I'm not sure I read any comments that said that JAKE was a weak answer to the given clue.  I think people said that they weren't familiar with the use of JAKE in that sense, and perhaps they didn't know copacetic, either.

In any event, the clue has to fit the answer, not the other way around.  The grid is created first; then clues are written for each answer.

@Jess 

I don't know how long you've been solving the NYT crossword, but keep at it. Many of us started out disliking Thursday trickery, but now enjoy it.

Good luck and have fun!

@Lesley 

Martin Luther King, Jr. and John F. Kennedy were cut down in the prime of their lives. 

Does that work for you?

@Aaron 

Thursdays are the ones that make you think outside the grid (sometimes literally). There are many of us who enjoy the challenges presented by Thursday puzzles, which have included rebuses, hidden letters, backwards spelling, and more. I'm amazed as to what constructors have come up with, and the fact that most of us have figured out how to solve them. And no, we don't want to know the theme until we figure it out. It's called a puzzle for a reason.

If you're strictly a casual solver, I'd suggest sticking to Sun.-Wed. puzzles, where the themes are going to be a little more obvious.
